Following that, `kdamond_fn` (which calls `kdamond_call`) exits its main loop, and then a call to `kdamond_call(ctx, true)` occurs (cancellation). Now, the same logic executes, but with the intent to cancel the controls. This cancellation call gathers the remaining controls, Control B. It marks Control B as canceled and calls `complete(&control->completion)`. Then it breaks after completing control B because `ctx->maybe_corrupted` is *still* `true`. This leaves Control C untouched! It is still in `ctx->call_controls`, and has never been completed or cancelled!

